kname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Gwilyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwilim","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Gwillym","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilyn ap Madog was born in 1304, in Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales. She had at least 1 daughter with Gwilym Sais ap Madog. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1304–":"1304–Surnud","1302–1360":"1302–1360","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"1304–":"1304–Kuollut","1302–1360":"1302–1360","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1304–Female":"1304–Kuollut","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"1304–":"1304–Décédée","1302–1360":"1302–1360","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","1304–Female":"1304–Décédée","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Galles","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilyn ap Madog est née en 1304, à Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Galles. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Gwilym Sais ap Madog. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1304–":"1304–Verstorben","1302–1360":"1302–1360","1330–Female":"1330–Verstorben","1304–Female":"1304–Verstorben","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilyn ap Madog wurde 1304 in Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales geboren. Sie hatte mit Gwilym Sais ap Madog mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb in ihrem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1304–":"1304–Desede","1302–1360":"1302–1360","1330–Female":"1330–Desede","1304–Female":"1304–Desede","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales"},"hu":{"1304–":"1304–elhunyt","1302–1360":"1302–1360","1330–Female":"1330–elhunyt","1304–Female":"1304–elhunyt","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1330":"1330